1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,980
[SPEAKER_00] Hvala što pratite kanal.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:59,979
[SPEAKER_00] Hvala što pratite kanal.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] Hvala što pratite kanal.

4
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:06,879
[SPEAKER_00] as it was used by the fathers of the Council 1700 years ago

5
00:01:06,879 --> 00:01:11,359
[SPEAKER_00] to articulate the divine consubstantiality of the Son with the Father.

6
00:01:11,359 --> 00:01:15,099
[SPEAKER_00] During my presentation, I won't be reading the sources,

7
00:01:15,099 --> 00:01:18,620
[SPEAKER_00] but they will be displayed on the PowerPoints on the slides

8
00:01:18,620 --> 00:01:21,939
[SPEAKER_00] and can be easily referenced throughout the presentation.

9
00:01:21,939 --> 00:01:29,040
[SPEAKER_00] So, just to begin, approximately 75 years after the Council of Nicaea,

10
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:31,980
[SPEAKER_00] at the outset of composing De Trinitate,

11
00:01:31,980 --> 00:01:35,780
[SPEAKER_00] St. Augustine engaged in a public debate with Passentius,

12
00:01:35,780 --> 00:01:40,480
[SPEAKER_00] an Aryan member of the imperial court, concerning the term homoousius.

13
00:01:40,480 --> 00:01:45,700
[SPEAKER_00] During the debate, Passentius advanced a well-known argument against the term,

14
00:01:45,700 --> 00:01:49,579
[SPEAKER_00] asserting that homoousius does not appear in scripture.

15
00:01:49,579 --> 00:01:54,680
[SPEAKER_00] In response, Augustine offered a nuanced and strategic rebuttal.

16
00:01:54,680 --> 00:01:58,340
[SPEAKER_00] He first observed that, as a Greek term,

17
00:01:58,340 --> 00:02:02,599
[SPEAKER_00] homoousius would not be expected to appear in the Latin scripture.

18
00:02:02,599 --> 00:02:07,180
[SPEAKER_00] However, rather than focusing solely on the presence of the term,

19
00:02:07,180 --> 00:02:12,840
[SPEAKER_00] Augustine emphasized the importance of identifying its scriptural meaning.

20
00:02:12,840 --> 00:02:15,560
[SPEAKER_00] Regarding its semantic equivalents,

21
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:18,719
[SPEAKER_00] Augustine refrained from a straightforward translation,

22
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:24,280
[SPEAKER_00] noting that alternatives such as eiusdem substantia or una substantia

23
00:02:24,280 --> 00:02:26,680
[SPEAKER_00] might similarly be criticized

24
00:02:26,680 --> 00:02:31,360
[SPEAKER_00] for lacking direst scriptural attestation within the creed.

25
00:02:31,360 --> 00:02:35,340
[SPEAKER_00] Nonetheless, he argued that the concept itself,

26
00:02:35,340 --> 00:02:36,460
[SPEAKER_00] res ipsa,

27
00:02:36,460 --> 00:02:38,620
[SPEAKER_00] is indeed found in scripture.

28
00:02:38,620 --> 00:02:41,539
[SPEAKER_00] Specifically, Augustine identified

29
00:02:41,539 --> 00:02:43,599
[SPEAKER_00] Ego et pater unum sumus,

30
00:02:43,599 --> 00:02:46,699
[SPEAKER_00] as the Latin scriptural equivalent of homoousius.

31
00:02:46,699 --> 00:02:48,819
[SPEAKER_00] Through this interpretation,

32
00:02:48,819 --> 00:02:51,979
[SPEAKER_00] he asserted that the passage conveys the doctrinal truth

33
00:02:51,979 --> 00:02:56,219
[SPEAKER_00] that the father and the son share the same nature and substance.

34
00:02:56,219 --> 00:03:00,560
[SPEAKER_00] The aim of this paper is to examine the Trinitarian issues

35
00:03:00,560 --> 00:03:02,080
[SPEAKER_00] addressed by the First Council

36
00:03:02,080 --> 00:03:06,520
[SPEAKER_00] from the perspective of emerging Latin Christian literature.

37
00:03:07,479 --> 00:03:10,939
[SPEAKER_00] The question of alleged Western influences

38
00:03:10,939 --> 00:03:13,319
[SPEAKER_00] on the historical and theological proceedings

39
00:03:13,319 --> 00:03:15,180
[SPEAKER_00] of the First Council of Nicaea

40
00:03:15,180 --> 00:03:18,520
[SPEAKER_00] has been a long-standing topic of scholarly debate.

41
00:03:18,520 --> 00:03:19,939
[SPEAKER_00] Early on,

42
00:03:19,939 --> 00:03:22,580
[SPEAKER_00] the idea that Western theology influenced

43
00:03:22,580 --> 00:03:25,219
[SPEAKER_00] or even originated the Nicene Creed

44
00:03:25,219 --> 00:03:27,400
[SPEAKER_00] gained considerable support.

45
00:03:27,400 --> 00:03:30,259
[SPEAKER_00] Scholars such as Adolf von Harnack,

46
00:03:30,259 --> 00:03:32,139
[SPEAKER_00] Taudor Zahn and Gustav Krüger

47
00:03:32,139 --> 00:03:34,639
[SPEAKER_00] attempted to establish a connection

48
00:03:34,639 --> 00:03:36,479
[SPEAKER_00] between the strong emphasis

49
00:03:36,479 --> 00:03:37,639
[SPEAKER_00] on divine unity

50
00:03:37,639 --> 00:03:39,840
[SPEAKER_00] in the works of early Western theologians

51
00:03:39,840 --> 00:03:41,280
[SPEAKER_00] like Tertullian

52
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] and the content of the Nicene Creed.

53
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,840
[SPEAKER_00] However, over the past 50 years,

54
00:03:46,840 --> 00:03:49,539
[SPEAKER_00] this theory has been seriously challenged

55
00:03:49,539 --> 00:03:52,259
[SPEAKER_00] and subjected to significant criticism,

56
00:03:52,259 --> 00:03:55,340
[SPEAKER_00] particularly with the work of Christopher Steed,

57
00:03:55,340 --> 00:03:57,500
[SPEAKER_00] his work Divine Substance.

58
00:03:57,500 --> 00:03:59,900
[SPEAKER_00] I would argue that the proceedings

59
00:03:59,900 --> 00:04:01,860
[SPEAKER_00] of the Council of Nicaea involved

60
00:04:01,860 --> 00:04:04,280
[SPEAKER_00] considerable input from Western theology

61
00:04:04,280 --> 00:04:06,419
[SPEAKER_00] and that, at the very least,

62
00:04:06,419 --> 00:04:09,180
[SPEAKER_00] Western influence cannot be dismissed.

63
00:04:09,180 --> 00:04:13,400
[SPEAKER_00] To assess the extent of this Latin influence,

64
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:16,519
[SPEAKER_00] it is crucial to first examine

65
00:04:16,519 --> 00:04:18,279
[SPEAKER_00] the role of Hosseus of Cordoba

66
00:04:18,279 --> 00:04:20,060
[SPEAKER_00] in the Council's proceedings,

67
00:04:20,060 --> 00:04:23,279
[SPEAKER_00] as well as the origins of the term Homo usios,

68
00:04:23,279 --> 00:04:26,480
[SPEAKER_00] specifically whether Latin theological thought

69
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:28,680
[SPEAKER_00] played a formative role in its adoption.

70
00:04:29,220 --> 00:04:31,139
[SPEAKER_00] Additionally, a broader examination

71
00:04:31,139 --> 00:04:33,160
[SPEAKER_00] of the Latin theological tradition

72
00:04:33,160 --> 00:04:36,199
[SPEAKER_00] from Tertullian to Hilary is necessary.

73
00:04:36,199 --> 00:04:38,220
[SPEAKER_00] By analysing this tradition

74
00:04:38,220 --> 00:04:40,259
[SPEAKER_00] in the context of the Nicene Council,

75
00:04:40,259 --> 00:04:42,860
[SPEAKER_00] albeit in a preliminary manner,

76
00:04:42,860 --> 00:04:45,139
[SPEAKER_00] we may gain a deeper understanding

77
00:04:45,139 --> 00:04:47,420
[SPEAKER_00] of its potential contributions

78
00:04:47,420 --> 00:04:50,139
[SPEAKER_00] to the development of the Trinitarian doctrine.

79
00:04:50,139 --> 00:04:52,759
[SPEAKER_00] So it is crucial to begin

80
00:04:52,759 --> 00:04:55,279
[SPEAKER_00] by examining the role of Hosseus of Cordoba,

81
00:04:55,279 --> 00:04:56,980
[SPEAKER_00] who served as the president

82
00:04:56,980 --> 00:04:58,860
[SPEAKER_00] of the Council of Nicaea

83
00:04:58,860 --> 00:05:01,519
[SPEAKER_00] and an advisor to Emperor Constantine.

84
00:05:01,519 --> 00:05:05,060
[SPEAKER_00] In 324, he was sent by the emperor

85
00:05:05,060 --> 00:05:07,699
[SPEAKER_00] to Alexandria to mediate the conflict

86
00:05:07,699 --> 00:05:09,819
[SPEAKER_00] between Alexander and Arius.

87
00:05:09,819 --> 00:05:13,160
[SPEAKER_00] He later presided over the Synod of Antioch

88
00:05:13,160 --> 00:05:16,120
[SPEAKER_00] in 325, as well as the councils

89
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:19,980
[SPEAKER_00] of Cernica 342 and Sirmium 358.

90
00:05:19,980 --> 00:05:22,680
[SPEAKER_00] In recent years, however,

91
00:05:22,680 --> 00:05:25,920
[SPEAKER_00] new perspectives have emerged,

92
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:27,699
[SPEAKER_00] particularly through the work

93
00:05:27,699 --> 00:05:29,319
[SPEAKER_00] of Brian Herbert Warmington.

94
00:05:29,319 --> 00:05:31,819
[SPEAKER_00] Warmington has challenged the notion

95
00:05:31,819 --> 00:05:33,699
[SPEAKER_00] that ecclesiastical figures,

96
00:05:33,699 --> 00:05:35,160
[SPEAKER_00] including Hosseus,

97
00:05:35,160 --> 00:05:38,240
[SPEAKER_00] could have held advisory positions

98
00:05:38,240 --> 00:05:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] within the emperor's inner council.

99
00:05:40,959 --> 00:05:43,120
[SPEAKER_00] Furthermore, based on the Eusebius sources,

100
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:46,160
[SPEAKER_00] he argues that Hosseus' role in these events

101
00:05:46,160 --> 00:05:48,060
[SPEAKER_00] may not have been as decisive

102
00:05:48,060 --> 00:05:49,959
[SPEAKER_00] as traditionally assumed.

103
00:05:49,959 --> 00:05:51,560
[SPEAKER_00] At the same time,

104
00:05:51,560 --> 00:05:53,160
[SPEAKER_00] Samuel Fernandes presents

105
00:05:53,160 --> 00:05:54,500
[SPEAKER_00] a compelling argument

106
00:05:54,500 --> 00:05:56,800
[SPEAKER_00] that Hosseus was the one

107
00:05:56,800 --> 00:05:58,259
[SPEAKER_00] who initiated the idea

108
00:05:58,259 --> 00:05:59,620
[SPEAKER_00] of convening the council

109
00:05:59,620 --> 00:06:01,199
[SPEAKER_00] and can be seen

110
00:06:01,199 --> 00:06:02,860
[SPEAKER_00] as its intellectual leader.

111
00:06:02,860 --> 00:06:05,480
[SPEAKER_00] Evidence for this can be found

112
00:06:05,480 --> 00:06:07,439
[SPEAKER_00] in the letter of the Synod of Antioch,

113
00:06:07,779 --> 00:06:09,519
[SPEAKER_00] written before Hosseus' supposed

114
00:06:09,519 --> 00:06:11,139
[SPEAKER_00] peace mission had concluded,

115
00:06:11,139 --> 00:06:13,399
[SPEAKER_00] that is, before his return

116
00:06:13,399 --> 00:06:14,300
[SPEAKER_00] to Nicomedia.

117
00:06:14,300 --> 00:06:16,899
[SPEAKER_00] This letter mentions plans

118
00:06:16,899 --> 00:06:18,680
[SPEAKER_00] for a great and priestly synod

119
00:06:18,680 --> 00:06:19,639
[SPEAKER_00] in Ankura,

120
00:06:19,639 --> 00:06:21,980
[SPEAKER_00] which was intended to offer

121
00:06:21,980 --> 00:06:23,360
[SPEAKER_00] a place for repentance

122
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:24,680
[SPEAKER_00] for the condemned bishops,

123
00:06:24,680 --> 00:06:26,399
[SPEAKER_00] including Eusebius.

124
00:06:26,399 --> 00:06:28,779
[SPEAKER_00] It seems that Hosseus had

125
00:06:28,779 --> 00:06:30,480
[SPEAKER_00] the authority and autonomy

126
00:06:30,480 --> 00:06:33,199
[SPEAKER_00] to independently convene the council

127
00:06:33,199 --> 00:06:36,079
[SPEAKER_00] based on his synodal experience,

128
00:06:36,540 --> 00:06:38,120
[SPEAKER_00] addressing the doctrinal divisions

129
00:06:38,120 --> 00:06:39,939
[SPEAKER_00] threatening the unity of the Church.

130
00:06:39,939 --> 00:06:41,920
[SPEAKER_00] While Sosamon states

131
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:43,860
[SPEAKER_00] that Constantine convened the synod

132
00:06:43,860 --> 00:06:45,399
[SPEAKER_00] following Hosseus' return,

133
00:06:45,399 --> 00:06:47,079
[SPEAKER_00] Rufinus suggests

134
00:06:47,079 --> 00:06:49,420
[SPEAKER_00] that the decision was made

135
00:06:49,420 --> 00:06:51,120
[SPEAKER_00] on the advice of the bishops.

136
00:06:51,120 --> 00:06:52,620
[SPEAKER_00] Notably,

137
00:06:52,620 --> 00:06:54,500
[SPEAKER_00] Sopisius Severus confirms

138
00:06:54,500 --> 00:06:55,860
[SPEAKER_00] Hosseus' central role,

139
00:06:55,860 --> 00:06:58,040
[SPEAKER_00] stating that the Nicene council

140
00:06:58,040 --> 00:07:00,600
[SPEAKER_00] was convened under his authority.

141
00:07:00,600 --> 00:07:03,540
[SPEAKER_00] The discrepancies among sources

142
00:07:03,540 --> 00:07:05,519
[SPEAKER_00] can likely be attributed

143
00:07:05,519 --> 00:07:06,480
[SPEAKER_00] to Eusebius,

144
00:07:06,480 --> 00:07:08,019
[SPEAKER_00] whose account became

145
00:07:08,019 --> 00:07:09,920
[SPEAKER_00] the dominant historical narrative.

146
00:07:09,920 --> 00:07:12,779
[SPEAKER_00] Eusebius deliberately omits

147
00:07:12,779 --> 00:07:14,399
[SPEAKER_00] reference to Hosseus' mission

148
00:07:14,399 --> 00:07:16,139
[SPEAKER_00] and the synod of Antioch,

149
00:07:16,139 --> 00:07:19,399
[SPEAKER_00] likely due to his excommunication there.

150
00:07:19,399 --> 00:07:21,399
[SPEAKER_00] And he also ignores the plan

151
00:07:21,399 --> 00:07:23,420
[SPEAKER_00] for a priestly synod of Ankura,

152
00:07:23,420 --> 00:07:25,980
[SPEAKER_00] instead presenting the council of Nicaea

153
00:07:25,980 --> 00:07:27,920
[SPEAKER_00] as solely Constantine's initiative.

154
00:07:28,920 --> 00:07:29,639
[SPEAKER_00] Collectively,

155
00:07:29,639 --> 00:07:30,459
[SPEAKER_00] these factors,

156
00:07:30,459 --> 00:07:31,439
[SPEAKER_00] in my view,

157
00:07:31,439 --> 00:07:33,620
[SPEAKER_00] strongly support the conclusion

158
00:07:33,620 --> 00:07:35,759
[SPEAKER_00] that Hosseus was the driving force

159
00:07:35,759 --> 00:07:37,360
[SPEAKER_00] behind the convocation

160
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:38,519
[SPEAKER_00] of what would become

161
00:07:38,519 --> 00:07:40,300
[SPEAKER_00] the first council of Nicaea.

162
00:07:40,300 --> 00:07:42,699
[SPEAKER_00] As the letter of the Antiochian synod

163
00:07:42,699 --> 00:07:43,480
[SPEAKER_00] reinforces,

164
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:45,160
[SPEAKER_00] he had the authority

165
00:07:45,160 --> 00:07:45,980
[SPEAKER_00] and autonomy

166
00:07:45,980 --> 00:07:47,879
[SPEAKER_00] to convene and preside

167
00:07:47,879 --> 00:07:49,180
[SPEAKER_00] over such a council.

168
00:07:49,180 --> 00:07:52,079
[SPEAKER_00] As previously mentioned,

169
00:07:52,079 --> 00:07:53,139
[SPEAKER_00] Homo Hosseus

170
00:07:53,139 --> 00:07:55,339
[SPEAKER_00] is one of the most significant terms

171
00:07:55,339 --> 00:07:57,459
[SPEAKER_00] introduced at the Council of Nicaea,

172
00:07:58,040 --> 00:07:59,779
[SPEAKER_00] expressing the substantial unity

173
00:07:59,779 --> 00:08:01,319
[SPEAKER_00] of the Son with the Father

174
00:08:01,319 --> 00:08:03,319
[SPEAKER_00] in a Trinitarian context.

175
00:08:03,319 --> 00:08:05,839
[SPEAKER_00] Our understanding of its use

176
00:08:05,839 --> 00:08:07,019
[SPEAKER_00] in the Nicene Creed

177
00:08:07,019 --> 00:08:08,360
[SPEAKER_00] is primarily informed

178
00:08:08,360 --> 00:08:10,079
[SPEAKER_00] by three key sources,

179
00:08:10,079 --> 00:08:12,899
[SPEAKER_00] the accounts of Eusebius of Caesarea,

180
00:08:12,899 --> 00:08:14,120
[SPEAKER_00] Athanasius,

181
00:08:14,120 --> 00:08:15,399
[SPEAKER_00] and Saint Ambrose.

182
00:08:15,399 --> 00:08:17,100
[SPEAKER_00] In the Fide,

183
00:08:17,100 --> 00:08:18,240
[SPEAKER_00] Ambrose of Milan

184
00:08:18,240 --> 00:08:20,019
[SPEAKER_00] attributes the origin of the term

185
00:08:20,019 --> 00:08:21,720
[SPEAKER_00] to Eusebius of Nicomedia,

186
00:08:21,720 --> 00:08:23,980
[SPEAKER_00] who in a letter read

187
00:08:23,980 --> 00:08:24,740
[SPEAKER_00] that the council

188
00:08:24,740 --> 00:08:27,160
[SPEAKER_00] explicitly rejected Homo Hosseus

189
00:08:27,160 --> 00:08:29,079
[SPEAKER_00] condemning it

190
00:08:29,079 --> 00:08:30,279
[SPEAKER_00] as unacceptable

191
00:08:30,279 --> 00:08:31,720
[SPEAKER_00] due to its perceived

192
00:08:31,720 --> 00:08:33,360
[SPEAKER_00] Saberlian connotations.

193
00:08:33,360 --> 00:08:35,480
[SPEAKER_00] According to Ambrose,

194
00:08:35,480 --> 00:08:36,679
[SPEAKER_00] the Nicene fathers

195
00:08:36,679 --> 00:08:38,360
[SPEAKER_00] adopted the term largely

196
00:08:38,360 --> 00:08:39,960
[SPEAKER_00] for polemical reasons,

197
00:08:39,960 --> 00:08:41,820
[SPEAKER_00] using it to counter

198
00:08:41,820 --> 00:08:43,500
[SPEAKER_00] the Arian theologians

199
00:08:43,500 --> 00:08:44,960
[SPEAKER_00] who had explicitly

200
00:08:44,960 --> 00:08:46,860
[SPEAKER_00] rejected Homo Hosseus.

201
00:08:46,860 --> 00:08:48,700
[SPEAKER_00] On the other hand,

202
00:08:48,700 --> 00:08:50,179
[SPEAKER_00] Athanasius credits

203
00:08:50,179 --> 00:08:51,299
[SPEAKER_00] Hosseus of Cordoba

204
00:08:51,299 --> 00:08:52,799
[SPEAKER_00] with drafting the creed

205
00:08:52,799 --> 00:08:54,059
[SPEAKER_00] that was ultimately

206
00:08:54,059 --> 00:08:55,639
[SPEAKER_00] adopted by Nicaea,

207
00:08:55,639 --> 00:08:57,039
[SPEAKER_00] suggesting that

208
00:08:57,039 --> 00:08:58,759
[SPEAKER_00] as president of the council

209
00:08:58,759 --> 00:09:00,259
[SPEAKER_00] he was responsible

210
00:09:00,259 --> 00:09:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] for introducing the term.

211
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:03,899
[SPEAKER_00] This claim appears

212
00:09:03,899 --> 00:09:05,059
[SPEAKER_00] to be corroborated

213
00:09:05,059 --> 00:09:06,419
[SPEAKER_00] by the Arian historian

214
00:09:06,419 --> 00:09:07,500
[SPEAKER_00] Philostorgius,

215
00:09:07,500 --> 00:09:08,799
[SPEAKER_00] who reports that

216
00:09:08,799 --> 00:09:10,139
[SPEAKER_00] Hosseus and Alexander

217
00:09:10,139 --> 00:09:11,360
[SPEAKER_00] of Alexandria

218
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:13,480
[SPEAKER_00] agreed on this concept

219
00:09:13,480 --> 00:09:15,120
[SPEAKER_00] and jointly proposed

220
00:09:15,120 --> 00:09:16,080
[SPEAKER_00] it to the council.

221
00:09:17,279 --> 00:09:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] Nevertheless,

222
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:20,159
[SPEAKER_00] while political factors

223
00:09:20,159 --> 00:09:21,399
[SPEAKER_00] may have influenced

224
00:09:21,399 --> 00:09:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] Hosseus,

225
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:23,600
[SPEAKER_00] particularly his role

226
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:24,519
[SPEAKER_00] as a mediator

227
00:09:24,519 --> 00:09:25,840
[SPEAKER_00] between conflicting

228
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:26,519
[SPEAKER_00] factions,

229
00:09:26,519 --> 00:09:28,399
